So therefore, let's
now talk about a method

01:02:00.550 --> 01:02:06.120
how we can entangle
atoms by using light.

01:02:06.120 --> 01:02:08.540
So if you take
atoms, maybe we can

01:02:08.540 --> 01:02:10.630
use the light which
has been emitted

01:02:10.630 --> 01:02:13.770
from the atoms, performing
measurement on the light,

01:02:13.770 --> 01:02:17.730
and then depending on the
outcome of the measurement,

01:02:17.730 --> 01:02:20.795
we know the atoms are entangled.

01:02:25.710 --> 01:02:35.770
So Professor [? Swann ?] calls
this the poor man's entangler.

01:02:38.510 --> 01:02:39.830
I don't know why poor man's.

01:02:39.830 --> 01:02:43.160
You still need quite a
bit of equipment to do it.

01:02:43.160 --> 01:02:46.250
But at least it seems
the poor man's solution

01:02:46.250 --> 01:02:49.680
if you can't make the
above experiment work.

01:02:49.680 --> 01:02:55.280
So this addresses
a question that,

01:02:55.280 --> 01:03:05.330
just for technical
reasons matter

01:03:05.330 --> 01:03:07.900
is more difficult to entangle.

01:03:11.300 --> 01:03:12.830
Whereas photons are easy.

01:03:28.640 --> 01:03:34.360
Yeah so you can say
the idea is related

01:03:34.360 --> 01:03:36.290
to the purification scheme.

01:03:36.290 --> 01:03:45.680
We can't take a system of two
atoms, atom one and atom two

01:03:45.680 --> 01:03:51.810
which are unentangled, and we
shine some laser light on them,

01:03:51.810 --> 01:03:52.890
excite them.

01:03:52.890 --> 01:03:54.780
Then they emit photons.

01:03:54.780 --> 01:03:57.520
So all we can do
is-- we can only

01:03:57.520 --> 01:03:59.260
talk to the atoms
with the photons.

01:03:59.260 --> 01:04:00.790
So the only thing
we can do now is

01:04:00.790 --> 01:04:02.830
we can measure the two photons.

01:04:02.830 --> 01:04:06.380
And then the situation will be
similar as in the purification

01:04:06.380 --> 01:04:09.170
scheme, where Alice and
Bob did a measurement.

01:04:09.170 --> 01:04:15.140
If Alice and Bob said both
of our target qubits are one,

01:04:15.140 --> 01:04:21.940
then what was left behind was
in a pure, entangled Bell state.

01:04:21.940 --> 01:04:25.560
And similarly, what you want to
do here is we have two atoms.

01:04:25.560 --> 01:04:28.940
There was nothing special about
them but they scatter light.

01:04:28.940 --> 01:04:32.480
And if you now perform a
measurement on the photons

01:04:32.480 --> 01:04:36.030
and the outcome of the
measurement is positive,

01:04:36.030 --> 01:04:39.800
then we know for sure what has
been left behind is entangled.

01:04:39.800 --> 01:04:42.420
That's the idea.

01:04:42.420 --> 01:04:46.560
So it shares with the
purification scheme

01:04:46.560 --> 01:04:48.610
that it is a probabilistic
entanglement.

01:04:48.610 --> 01:04:51.090
You run your
experiment many times.

01:04:51.090 --> 01:04:52.062
You do a measurement.

01:04:52.062 --> 01:04:53.520
If the measurement
is positive, you

01:04:53.520 --> 01:04:55.340
say now I have an
entangled state.

01:04:55.340 --> 01:04:58.220
And maybe then you can move on
to measure the entanglement.

01:04:58.220 --> 01:05:01.815
You can move on to do
teleportation, other things you

01:05:01.815 --> 01:05:03.190
want to do with
entangled states.

01:05:03.190 --> 01:05:07.035
But if your measurements
says no, bad luck.

01:05:07.035 --> 01:05:09.770
The probability hasn't
worked out this time.

01:05:09.770 --> 01:05:12.150
You just press a button
again, scatter light

01:05:12.150 --> 01:05:14.209
again of your two atoms
and/or your two ions

01:05:14.209 --> 01:05:16.000
and hope that the next
outcome is positive.

01:05:20.990 --> 01:05:26.780
So the idea is we
want to introduce now

01:05:26.780 --> 01:05:31.550
a probabilistic method.

01:05:39.390 --> 01:05:44.355
It's based on two
atoms emitting light.

01:05:48.070 --> 01:05:52.170
And the result is with
a certain probability

01:05:52.170 --> 01:05:53.690
that we get entangled atoms.

01:06:30.320 --> 01:06:36.036
Let me just scroll down and
show you one thing I want to--

01:06:46.790 --> 01:06:49.170
When I prepare the notes and
everything is clear to me,

01:06:49.170 --> 01:06:51.260
but then I want to explain
it to you and say hey,

01:06:51.260 --> 01:06:52.480
I have to motivate you.

01:06:52.480 --> 01:06:54.110
If I just go
through a few lines,

01:06:54.110 --> 01:06:55.550
you wonder what it leads to.

01:06:55.550 --> 01:06:57.600
So let me maybe first
give you the explanation

01:06:57.600 --> 01:06:59.350
I would have given you
a little bit later.

01:07:03.750 --> 01:07:07.160
What is an entangled
state is if the atoms are

01:07:07.160 --> 01:07:10.870
in maybe one of two ground
states-- one atom is in one

01:07:10.870 --> 01:07:13.990
ground state, the other
one is in the other one,

01:07:13.990 --> 01:07:15.490
or it is flipped.

01:07:15.490 --> 01:07:18.430
So we know one atom is
in the ground state one.

01:07:18.430 --> 01:07:20.640
One atom is in the
ground state two,

01:07:20.640 --> 01:07:22.350
but we don't know
which one is in which.

01:07:22.350 --> 01:07:25.320
It is in the
superposition state.

01:07:25.320 --> 01:07:28.100
So what you need
now in this scheme

01:07:28.100 --> 01:07:32.270
is the following-- if
the atoms scatter light,

01:07:32.270 --> 01:07:35.840
they can go to two
different ground states.

01:07:40.200 --> 01:07:43.600
And we know to
which ground state

01:07:43.600 --> 01:07:47.320
they have gone, because
due to selection rules,

01:07:47.320 --> 01:07:50.050
they reach one ground state
with polarization one.

01:07:50.050 --> 01:07:53.310
They reach one ground state
with polarization two.

01:07:53.310 --> 01:07:56.840
So therefore, when we had
two atoms, they emit light

01:07:56.840 --> 01:07:59.480
and we would measure the
polarization of the light,

01:07:59.480 --> 01:08:01.340
we would know in
which state they are.

01:08:01.340 --> 01:08:03.570
But if you know atom
1 is in state 1,

01:08:03.570 --> 01:08:06.940
and atom 2 is in state
2, this is not entangled.

01:08:06.940 --> 01:08:10.010
So what we have to do is when
the two atoms have emitted

01:08:10.010 --> 01:08:14.590
photons, we have to mix the
photon at the beam splitter.

01:08:14.590 --> 01:08:16.500
And after the beam
splitter, when

01:08:16.500 --> 01:08:19.420
we measure that the
photon is polarized,

01:08:19.420 --> 01:08:23.710
we know that one of the atoms
is in one of the ground states,

01:08:23.710 --> 01:08:25.470
but we don't know which.

01:08:25.470 --> 01:08:31.069
So therefore, we can now
use-- the photon carries

01:08:31.069 --> 01:08:35.510
through the polarization the
information in which ground

01:08:35.510 --> 01:08:37.270
state the atom is.

01:08:37.270 --> 01:08:40.790
But now we have to perform
operations to the photons

01:08:40.790 --> 01:08:44.680
that for fundamental
reasons, fundamental quantum

01:08:44.680 --> 01:08:48.310
measurement, we know there
is one photon in one state,

01:08:48.310 --> 01:08:50.910
but we have no way
to ever figure out

01:08:50.910 --> 01:08:54.220
which atom has
emitted the photon.

01:08:54.220 --> 01:08:56.170
So that's the idea,
and the protocol

01:08:56.170 --> 01:08:59.130
I want to show you now is what
do we have to do to the two

01:08:59.130 --> 01:09:02.390
photons to make sure
that we never know,

01:09:02.390 --> 01:09:06.130
that we can't find out which
atom has emitted the photon.

01:09:06.130 --> 01:09:08.210
And we have to do little
bit more tricks also

01:09:08.210 --> 01:09:10.930
to make sure that when we do
a measurement on the photon,

01:09:10.930 --> 01:09:14.870
we know the atoms are
in the Bell state.

01:09:14.870 --> 01:09:15.830
Questions about that?

01:09:37.899 --> 01:09:41.254
So therefore, we
need a beam splitter.

01:09:45.689 --> 01:09:48.870
So we can come back to
what we have already

01:09:48.870 --> 01:09:50.274
introduced in the last section.

01:09:58.540 --> 01:10:02.990
So each atom will emit a photon.

01:10:02.990 --> 01:10:07.020
And I will actually show
you at the end of the class

01:10:07.020 --> 01:10:09.350
that people have
entangled with that scheme

01:10:09.350 --> 01:10:12.000
two ions which were in
two different ion traps.

01:10:12.000 --> 01:10:14.290
So you have two distance atoms.

01:10:14.290 --> 01:10:16.960
They emit light, and after
the measurement process,

01:10:16.960 --> 01:10:18.190
you know they are entangled.

01:10:18.190 --> 01:10:19.990
And that's pretty cool.

01:10:19.990 --> 01:10:24.190
So the situation how we do it is
we have two photons which come.

01:10:24.190 --> 01:10:26.130
But the first thing
we have to make sure

01:10:26.130 --> 01:10:28.250
is we have to
scramble the photons.

01:10:28.250 --> 01:10:30.190
We have to make sure
that we can't find out

01:10:30.190 --> 01:10:32.470
from which atom the
photon has come,

01:10:32.470 --> 01:10:35.320
and this is done with
the beam splitter.

01:10:35.320 --> 01:10:38.330
So there is one aspect
of beam splitters

01:10:38.330 --> 01:10:41.710
and two photons which have
to explain to you now.

01:10:41.710 --> 01:10:49.620
And this is this famous
HUM, Hong-Ou-Mandel.

01:10:52.540 --> 01:11:00.430
This is the Hong-Ou-Mandel
interference.

01:11:00.430 --> 01:11:02.480
It's a very famous
effect, and it's actually

01:11:02.480 --> 01:11:04.140
very, very special.

01:11:04.140 --> 01:11:07.280
So let me explain
what happens when

01:11:07.280 --> 01:11:13.160
we have two photons
in the same state--

01:11:13.160 --> 01:11:18.327
two identical photons, same
frequency, same polarization--

01:11:18.327 --> 01:11:19.410
coming to a beam splitter.

01:11:28.820 --> 01:11:32.010
So we have already
all the tools.

01:11:32.010 --> 01:11:35.050
So we have a beam
splitter characterized

01:11:35.050 --> 01:11:37.560
by this angle theta, which
through cosine theta,

01:11:37.560 --> 01:11:40.930
sine theta determines what
the beam splitter is doing.

01:11:40.930 --> 01:11:46.730
And all we want to do is we
apply it now to the state 1 1.

01:11:49.790 --> 01:11:54.190
So what we will find is
that there is a probability

01:11:54.190 --> 01:11:58.050
to get one photon each.

01:11:58.050 --> 01:12:03.140
Then there is a probability to
get two photons in one output.

01:12:03.140 --> 01:12:06.010
And it will actually
be the same probability

01:12:06.010 --> 01:12:10.370
with a minus sign in the
amplitude to get 0 2.

01:12:10.370 --> 01:12:14.120
And the matrix which acts
on each of the photons

01:12:14.120 --> 01:12:17.040
has cosines and sines.

01:12:17.040 --> 01:12:25.690
So what we get is products
of trigonometric functions.

01:12:25.690 --> 01:12:31.370
And here for getting
two photons in one arm,

01:12:31.370 --> 01:12:41.390
it's square root 2,
cosine theta, sine theta.

01:12:43.940 --> 01:12:48.680
And the spectacular
thing here is

01:12:48.680 --> 01:12:52.090
what happens when we have
a balanced beam splitter.

01:13:06.770 --> 01:13:11.510
If you have the
50-50 beam splitter--

01:13:11.510 --> 01:13:15.040
and this is called the
Hong-Ou-Mandel interference,

01:13:15.040 --> 01:13:23.630
you have the situation where
you have a beam splitter,

01:13:23.630 --> 01:13:28.840
you have one photon,
you have two photons.

01:13:28.840 --> 01:13:34.560
And it is absolutely
impossible that afterwards, you

01:13:34.560 --> 01:13:36.590
have one photon in each arm.

01:13:36.590 --> 01:13:40.210
So you send two photons
on a beam splitter,

01:13:40.210 --> 01:13:42.890
and after the beam
splitter is, you

01:13:42.890 --> 01:13:46.190
have either two photons
coming out here,

01:13:46.190 --> 01:13:48.470
or two photons coming out there.

01:13:52.470 --> 01:13:56.630
You can say it's Poissonic
stimulation photons and bosons.

01:13:56.630 --> 01:13:58.010
That all plays a role.

01:13:58.010 --> 01:14:02.500
If one photon goes one path,
the other photons follow suit.

01:14:06.910 --> 01:14:10.970
This is now very powerful,
because it already

01:14:10.970 --> 01:14:14.620
happens, of course, when the
two photons are identical.

01:14:14.620 --> 01:14:17.840
We had to use in this
formalism the photon is

01:14:17.840 --> 01:14:20.030
in the same mode on each part.

01:14:20.030 --> 01:14:22.560
But that means now
the following--

01:14:22.560 --> 01:14:25.340
if you set up photo
detectors here,

01:14:25.340 --> 01:14:28.260
and each photon
detector makes click,

01:14:28.260 --> 01:14:30.850
you know you had
one photon each.

01:14:30.850 --> 01:14:36.310
And that tells you that the two
photons were not identical--

01:14:36.310 --> 01:14:40.380
for instance, because they
have different polarizations.

01:14:40.380 --> 01:14:41.980
So if you want to
now, with the atoms,

01:14:41.980 --> 01:14:44.840
get a Bell state, where
atoms decay-- one atom

01:14:44.840 --> 01:14:47.110
decays to state
one, one atom decays

01:14:47.110 --> 01:14:51.160
to state two-- the
signature of that

01:14:51.160 --> 01:14:55.050
would be that we
have one atom each.

01:14:55.050 --> 01:15:04.660
And if you do it right, one atom
each is an ingredient for 1 2

01:15:04.660 --> 01:15:06.780
plus 2 1 for Bell state.

01:15:06.780 --> 01:15:10.010
We can detect that we have one
photon each because at such

01:15:10.010 --> 01:15:13.260
a beam splitter, it's
only in this situation

01:15:13.260 --> 01:15:16.500
that we can get one photon
after each beam splitter

01:15:16.500 --> 01:15:21.020
if we start with two
non-identical photons.

01:15:21.020 --> 01:15:24.990
Of course, by the way,
experimentally there are quite

01:15:24.990 --> 01:15:28.130
some challenges, even if
you have identical photons

01:15:28.130 --> 01:15:31.870
of the same polarization, if
they arrive as a nanosecond

01:15:31.870 --> 01:15:35.710
pulse, and they don't arrive
exactly at the same time

01:15:35.710 --> 01:15:39.390
at the beam splitter, then
you first split one photon,

01:15:39.390 --> 01:15:41.800
and then the next photon,
and the two photons cannot

01:15:41.800 --> 01:15:43.330
influence each other.

01:15:43.330 --> 01:15:46.030
So there are a lot of
experimental requirements

01:15:46.030 --> 01:15:48.065
to realize this
ideal experiment.

01:15:57.340 --> 01:16:02.590
So as I was preparing
for today's class,

01:16:02.590 --> 01:16:12.317
I actually saw a paper which
just came out in "Science."

01:16:32.390 --> 01:16:35.750
So in this month's
"Science" they

01:16:35.750 --> 01:16:39.215
discussed the Hong-Ou-Mandel
interference experiment

01:16:39.215 --> 01:16:41.440
with fermions.

01:16:41.440 --> 01:16:44.150
So let me just
explain what happens.

01:17:11.930 --> 01:17:12.783
OK, now it fits.

01:17:21.330 --> 01:17:24.720
So if you have two
identical photons,

01:17:24.720 --> 01:17:29.530
if you have two particles which
impinge on the beam splitter--

01:17:29.530 --> 01:17:33.380
they are the two input beams
for the beam splitter--

01:17:33.380 --> 01:17:36.620
you would say you have
four different outcomes.

01:17:36.620 --> 01:17:40.630
One is both come out
here, both come out here.

01:17:40.630 --> 01:17:43.730
Or they are both
reflected, or they are both

01:17:43.730 --> 01:17:45.500
transmitted through.

01:17:45.500 --> 01:17:49.080
And what happens is bosons--
as I just pointed out--

01:17:49.080 --> 01:17:52.690
bosons characterized by
photons can only do that.

01:17:52.690 --> 01:17:55.430
Identical photons
want two bunch up.

01:17:55.430 --> 01:18:02.390
They appear in pairs-- 50%
left output, 50% right output.

01:18:02.390 --> 01:18:05.260
Well, for fermions, they
just do the opposite.

01:18:05.260 --> 01:18:08.680
For fermions, you will
always get one particle each.

01:18:08.680 --> 01:18:10.637
You may immediately,
of course, explain it

01:18:10.637 --> 01:18:12.720
with the Pauli Exclusion
Principle, which does not

01:18:12.720 --> 01:18:14.650
allow two particles to
be in the same state

01:18:14.650 --> 01:18:16.240
after the beam splitter.

01:18:16.240 --> 01:18:19.850
And you should contrast it
with classical particles.

01:18:19.850 --> 01:18:22.620
When you have two
classical particles,

01:18:22.620 --> 01:18:26.950
you will actually find that all
of those four possibilities,

01:18:26.950 --> 01:18:28.865
each of them has
a 25% probability.

01:18:31.560 --> 01:18:37.830
So it was a major
experiment which

01:18:37.830 --> 01:18:40.070
was featured in "Science"
when people realized

01:18:40.070 --> 01:18:42.720
that with electrons,
they created electrons

01:18:42.720 --> 01:18:48.950
in a semiconductor
structure, and showed

01:18:48.950 --> 01:18:53.210
through some
statistical measurement

01:18:53.210 --> 01:18:56.920
that this was the
physics which happened.

01:18:56.920 --> 01:18:59.090
The measurement they did
is, I forgot details--

01:18:59.090 --> 01:19:02.820
if you have bosons and you get
either two here or two there,

01:19:02.820 --> 01:19:05.720
you have more fluctuations in
your system than for fermions.

01:19:05.720 --> 01:19:07.810
And they conclusively
showed that they

01:19:07.810 --> 01:19:11.040
had realized the Hong-Ou-Mandel
interference for fermions.

01:19:37.390 --> 01:19:39.190
I think we have to stop.

01:19:39.190 --> 01:19:46.780
Let me just add one more
thing and then we are done.

01:19:50.070 --> 01:19:54.760
So this Hong-Ou-Mandel
interference

01:19:54.760 --> 01:19:59.640
is at the heart of how
perform the measurement which

01:19:59.640 --> 01:20:03.200
is ultimately
entangling the atoms.

01:20:03.200 --> 01:20:05.180
But we need one more element.

01:20:05.180 --> 01:20:09.130
We need sort of to scramble
the photons in one more way,

01:20:09.130 --> 01:20:17.860
and this is by adding circular
polarizers at the input.

01:20:17.860 --> 01:20:21.650
So we assume for now
that we start out

01:20:21.650 --> 01:20:26.860
with linear polarization
in those states.

01:20:26.860 --> 01:20:30.140
And here is our beam splitter.

01:20:30.140 --> 01:20:35.710
Here is mode a and mode
be, which we detect.

01:20:35.710 --> 01:20:42.990
And before we measure
this Hong interference,

01:20:42.990 --> 01:20:47.930
we put in quarter-wave
plates which

01:20:47.930 --> 01:20:49.900
provide circular polarization.

01:21:10.550 --> 01:21:13.120
If you start with linearly
polarized light-- we

01:21:13.120 --> 01:21:19.610
put in a polarizer-- after
the circular polarizer,

01:21:19.610 --> 01:21:21.640
we have this linear
superposition

01:21:21.640 --> 01:21:27.330
of horizontal and
vertical at mode one,

01:21:27.330 --> 01:21:30.130
and we have linear
polarization-- superposition

01:21:30.130 --> 01:21:34.340
of linear polarization
in mode two.

01:21:34.340 --> 01:21:42.100
So this is a situation at the
input of the beam splitter.

01:21:42.100 --> 01:21:47.440
And if we expand it,
we have probabilities

01:21:47.440 --> 01:21:51.860
where the polarization
is different,

01:21:51.860 --> 01:21:56.040
and where the
polarization is the same.

01:21:56.040 --> 01:21:59.280
So we have two detectors here.

01:21:59.280 --> 01:22:10.310
And if both detectors
click, then we

01:22:10.310 --> 01:22:16.050
know that the input
to the interferometer

01:22:16.050 --> 01:22:20.840
was not H H nor V V,
because in that case,

01:22:20.840 --> 01:22:23.820
the Hong-Ou-Mandel interference
would have directed

01:22:23.820 --> 01:22:27.300
both photons to one
output, and we would not

01:22:27.300 --> 01:22:29.950
have obtained clicks from both.

01:22:29.950 --> 01:22:34.840
So therefore, when
both detectors click,

01:22:34.840 --> 01:22:39.840
we know that the quantum state
before the interferometer--

01:22:39.840 --> 01:22:48.620
before the beam splitter-- was
H V or V H-- or, of course,

01:22:48.620 --> 01:22:53.200
in another basis, one of those.

01:22:53.200 --> 01:22:55.230
And this is sort of
the ingredient, which

01:22:55.230 --> 01:22:56.810
I will show you on
Wednesday, which

01:22:56.810 --> 01:23:00.230
can lead to probabilistic
entanglement of atoms.

01:23:00.230 --> 01:23:01.010
